node.text:
The best kind of #mondaymotivation 
from @effective.fitnesstraining
•
If this isn’t motivation to be a strong and prepared individual; I don’t know what is.

This is why it’s critical to prepare your body for high level performance. Multiple factors play into the physical development and growth of an individual: nutrition, programming, recovery, etc.

Remember, we can’t fail. Prepared to win. If you don’t know where to start we can help. LFG🏴

Backstory: 2 Officers in Yonkers, NY saved a baby stuck underneath a car. The incident occurred after an allegedly drunk driver drove into a building and hit the baby and her mother.

node.title: Hero officers lift car off of baby!

node.text:
We wish a very special thank you to all who served in the Vietnam war. We want to pay special tribute to a very dear friend of ours, Tom Eagles, who was an absolute hero, both to America, and to the Vietnamese people he dedicated his life to liberating. Tom passed away several years ago but his legacy still shines bright at NAR. He used to tell stories of tigers eating members of his patrol and surviving strafing runs by Cobra gunships who misidentified his team only because the canon malfunctioned so close to them they could see sparks inside of it from the short. Above all else, Tom was a pure and true believer in his mission. The atrocities committed by the Viet Cong against  those who aided him forever haunted him, as they did to many others who fought alongside him and throughout the conflict. We pause today to remember the sacrifices made by all the American service members who fought in those dark and scary jungles and those who didn’t make it home, both physically and mentally.

#vietnamwar #corpsman #macvsog #forcerecon #mat43 #veteran #vietnamveteran #neverforget

node.text:
Fire Suppression for first responders by @nardoctor . Goal is to stop the patient from burning, not to put out structure fires. Quick access and extraction of the patient WITHOUT becoming a burn patient yourself. Let the pros handle trying to save the house or car. For car and house fires select an ABC rated extinguisher (gasoline and electrical systems in the car). Majority are dry chemical, which is good for responders. Get one with a pressure gauge so you know it’s functional and inspect regularly. Make sure it is stored in an area that is readily accessible, consider multiple devices in different locations in case you cannot access one. Cooking fires at home are the most common so keep one nearby. 
.
Extinguishing a fire: If nobody is at risk, consider evacuating to safe location and letting fire department do its job. Stay upwind. Anything bigger than a waste basket size fire likely needs more you’re your extinguisher. Do not open the hood of a car engine fire. There are many inhalation hazards in fires so don’t be a hero. PASS= Pull pin, Aim low (base of fire focusing on where patient is and path to clear), Squeeze lever, Sweep side to side. Extinguishers don’t last long (less than 10 seconds for smaller ones) so efficiency is key. Do Not Use water for a grease fire. No extinguisher? use a fire blanket (nonflammable). Remember clothing- nylon/synthetic fibers melts to skin and creates bad burns. 
Continued in comments below ⤵️ 📹 by @chief_miller

node.text:
Young responder and his family who serves his community at a tiny department in remote Alaska who needs some love…

Last night Talkeetna Fire responded to a house fire for one of our own. Firefighter-EMT Andrew VanOrnum’s house was completely destroyed while he was transporting a patient to the hospital. His wife woke up to smoke and went down a flaming staircase with their 2 sons, Desmond 1, & Elisha 2 years old. No one was hurt but they escaped with only the clothes on their backs and have no insurance. Andrew drives Talkeetna Ambulance and responds to about 95% of calls. He has been with Fire Rescue and EMS since 2015.
We will have a separate Go Fund Me donation request in the next couple of days on Talkeetna Fire's Facebook page. The VanOrnum’s will be staying with friends for now so we will be looking for household & building supply items at a later date. This post is to help get them through the next month. Coordination for items to be dropped off at Talkeetna or Sunshine Fire station can be made with Chief Chappel at 907-841-3342.

They are looking for the following immediate needs:
Boys Clothes 18M and 2T, size 7 toddler shoes
Women’s Clothes - Medium Shirts - 8-10 size pants - size 9 shoes
Men’s Clothes - Medium Shirt - 30-32 pants - size 10 shoes
Looking for day-to-day clothes, jackets for all, etc.
Winter clothes will be needed before winter.
Diapers Size 3 Huggies preferred
Teething toys
Portable DVD Player and Winnie the Pooh DVDs (kids favorite show)
Kids toys (The boys love fire trucks and Winnie the Pooh

Gift Cards to Walmart, Target, Subway, or any other local restaurants. 

**They may be in need of a short-term rental if anyone knows of any in the Talkeetna area.

Donation spots have been setup at
Station 6-1 Wasilla
Houston Fire
Talkeetna fire’s post office box for small items gift cards etc. PO Box 285 Talkeetna 99676
Gift cards can be dropped off at Sarah’s gift cache at 408W 4th ave anchorage.

Campas left a lasting impression on his SWAT School instructors and classmates through his calm demeanor, dedication to his craft, and his uncanny ability to crack a joke to calm a stressful situation. node.text:
At a loss…

A man with a gun carjacked a Houston Fire Department ambulance with an EMT and a patient still inside early Friday, police said.

HFD Chief Samuel Peña said an EMT was driving the ambulance with a patient and another EMT in the back. As they were transporting the patient, an armed man firing shots forced the vehicle to stop. He pointed a gun at the EMT who was driving and took over the vehicle.

Thankfully, following a police pursuit, the hijacker was taken into custody without anyone inside the ambulance being injured.

The fire chief later praised the EMT for still being able to treat the patient and “deescalate” the situation, saying she did an “outstanding job.” He also praised HPD and criticized the suspect. 

“This is not part of their jobs — to be kidnapped, to be assaulted at gunpoint, but it definitely has become a risk of the job,” said Chief Peña early Friday. “We’re very thankful that everybody is okay, but it’s not acceptable for our firefighters and EMTs to be assaulted when their job is to go out there and make a positive impact.”

node.text:
If you are a hunter, you are acutely and excitedly aware that hunting season is looming. Injuries in the wild can be caused by a multitude of things ranging from the common to the exotic - the biggest take homes are ones we preach daily - get trained on basic bleeding control and carry basic kit on your person so you can either self rescue or help someone else in need!

from @spencerneuharth
•
WARNING: These photos are graphic. 
In October 2018, I slipped on my third to last treestand peg crawling down from an evening hunt. The fall was minimal—I was probably less than 5 feet off the ground. But the damage happened anyway. On the fall, my stomach caught a 4-inch steel tree step that opened me up. It was pretty damn painful, but I was able to hike a half mile back to the truck and drive myself 15 miles to the ER.
The doc said it was a mess to stitch because the wound was so random. He would have preferred I get cut by a knife rather than get jabbed by a steel rod. Still, he was able to get me back together with 13 stitches. 
I tell you this because it was a pretty scary and serious moment, but it wasn’t even good enough to make it in “MeatEater’s Campfire Stories: Close Calls.” This audio book exclusive has 16 near-death stories that are way, way better than mine (including a treestand fall from @bowhunting_fiend that caused temporary paralysis).
PS - The worst part wasn’t the pain or embarrassment—it was that this happened right before the rut. I had to take about 10 days off of hunting, but ended up killing four bucks in the next two months, including my second biggest whitetail ever.
#beprepared #fueledbynature
